\section{What a Lean Is}
% ============================================================

A lean is a trader's best estimate of the \textbf{true actionable liquidity} available for a given risk exposure at a given moment. It is not a theoretical fair value. It is not a model price. It answers a concrete question: \textit{if I needed to trade this exposure in the next 30 seconds, what price and size could I realistically get?}

The word ``lean'' comes from the idea that you \textit{lean on} observable liquidity to price and hedge related instruments. You observe where something is actually trading, and you use that observation as the foundation for everything else.

\begin{definition}[Lean Book]
A synthetic order book constructed by aggregating, cleaning, and converting observable liquidity across multiple venues and related instruments into a single unified view of the price and size available for a target instrument.
\end{definition}

The lean book is the \textbf{bottom layer} of the pricing stack. Everything else --- inventory management, alpha signals, client-specific adjustments --- sits on top. Get the lean wrong and everything downstream is wrong.


% ============================================================
\section{The Lean in Equities: The Clean Case}
% ============================================================

To understand the lean in bonds, start with the version that works cleanly in equities.

\subsection{Same-Instrument Lean: Collapsing Venues}

Consider NVDA. It trades on 10 lit exchanges and multiple dark venues. Each exchange shows an order book. But these 10 books do not all reflect the same ``real'' liquidity:

\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
  \item Some displayed size is from toxic market makers who will cancel before you can hit them.
  \item Each venue charges different take/make fees, so a \$185.00 bid on Exchange A has different economics than \$185.00 on Exchange B.
  \item Some price levels are too small to lean on --- a 100-share bid at \$185.01 is noise.
\end{itemize}

The lean book for NVDA collapses these 10 books into a single synthetic book by:

\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=2em]
  \item \textbf{Filtering} out price levels below a minimum size threshold.
  \item \textbf{Weighting} each venue's displayed size by a reliability factor (e.g., 0.8 if you estimate 20\% of liquidity is toxic and will fade).
  \item \textbf{Fee-adjusting} every price level to reflect the true economic cost of trading there.
  \item \textbf{Combining} the adjusted levels into a single depth-of-book.
\end{enumerate}

The result is a synthetic book that represents \textit{what you can actually trade}, not what the market displays.

\subsection{Cross-Instrument Lean: Pricing Related Assets}

This is where the lean becomes powerful. Once you have NVDA's lean book, you can price any instrument that shares the same risk exposure:

\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
  \item \textbf{NVDL} (2$\times$ leveraged NVDA ETF): quote it off the NVDA lean via $\text{NVDL} = 2 \times \text{NVDA} + \text{constant}$.
  \item \textbf{SPY, IVV, VOO} (all track the S\&P 500): each is a lean source for the others. Quote SPY by leaning on IVV and VOO.
\end{itemize}

The workflow is:

\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=2em]
  \item Observe the lean (liquid instrument's true actionable price).
  \item Convert to the target instrument via a known relationship.
  \item Quote the target off the converted lean.
  \item Get filled.
  \item Immediately hedge by trading the lean instrument.
  \item Capture the spread between your fill and your hedge.
\end{enumerate}

In equities, this works cleanly because the conversion is nearly perfect: SPY and IVV hold the same basket, so $Y = \beta X + c$ with $\beta$ known precisely and $c$ stable. The residual risk is tiny. You are essentially arbitraging a pricing dislocation between fungible instruments.

\subsection{The Equity Lean Stack}

The full pricing stack for an equity market maker:

\begin{verbatim}
  Layer 0:  Raw exchange books (10 venues for NVDA)
  Layer 1:  Clean each book (filter, weight, fee-adjust)
  Layer 2:  Collapse into a single lean book (same-instrument)
  Layer 3:  Price related instruments off the lean (cross-instrument)
  ---- above is the "lean" ----
  Layer 4:  Inventory lean (shade quotes to manage position)
  Layer 5:  Alpha signal (directional skew)
  ---- layers 4-5 are separate adjustments on top ----
\end{verbatim}

This document is about Layers 0--3: how to construct the lean itself. Layers 4--5 are covered in the companion strategy document.


