\section{Translating to Fixed Income}
% ============================================================

Every concept in the equity lean has a bond-market analogue, but each analogue is harder. This section maps them one by one and identifies where the translation breaks.

\subsection{Venue $\to$ Data Source}

In equities, a ``venue'' is a lit exchange with a visible, real-time order book. In bonds, there are no continuous order books for most names. The analogues are:

\begin{table}[h!]
\centering\small
\renewcommand{\arraystretch}{1.2}
\begin{tabular}{@{}p{4cm}p{4cm}p{4.5cm}@{}}
\toprule
\textbf{Equity Concept} & \textbf{Bond Analogue} & \textbf{Key Difference} \\
\midrule
Lit exchange book & TRACE prints & Historical (delayed), not live \\
& Composite quotes (CP+) & Indicative, smoothed, not firm \\
& Own RFQ responses & Real competitive prices, but sparse \\
& Dealer axes/runs & Directional signal, not firm \\
NBBO (best bid/offer) & No equivalent & No consolidated live quote \\
Real-time depth & No equivalent & Must be inferred from sparse data \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

The fundamental difference: in equities, you can \textit{see} the liquidity continuously. In bonds, you must \textit{infer} it from irregular, delayed, and incomplete observations.

\subsection{Fee Adjustment $\to$ Side and Spread Correction}

In equities, you adjust for venue fees (a fraction of a cent per share). In bonds, the analogue is correcting for the bid-ask spread embedded in observed transactions. A TRACE customer-buy print is a transaction at the dealer's offer, not at mid. To estimate mid, you must subtract the half-spread --- but the half-spread itself is uncertain, varies by bond, size, and market conditions, and is not directly observable.

\subsection{Toxic Liquidity Filtering $\to$ Staleness and Reliability Weighting}

In equities, you filter out toxic MMs who will cancel. In bonds, the analogue is weighting observations by freshness and reliability. A 3-hour-old TRACE print is ``stale liquidity'' --- it tells you where the bond traded, but not where it trades now. A composite quote that hasn't been updated in 2 minutes is suspect. Each observation gets a reliability weight that decays with age and varies by source quality.

\subsection{Cross-Instrument Lean $\to$ The Hard Part}

In equities, SPY $\leftrightarrow$ IVV is a nearly perfect conversion. In bonds, the cross-instrument relationships are:

\begin{table}[h!]
\centering\small
\renewcommand{\arraystretch}{1.2}
\begin{tabular}{@{}p{4cm}p{4cm}p{4.5cm}@{}}
\toprule
\textbf{Equity Analogue} & \textbf{Bond Relationship} & \textbf{Residual Risk} \\
\midrule
SPY $\leftrightarrow$ IVV (fungible) & On-the-run $\leftrightarrow$ off-the-run (same issuer, same maturity) & Small: liquidity premium difference \\
SPY $\leftrightarrow$ SPXL (leveraged) & Bond $\leftrightarrow$ CDS (same credit risk) & Medium: funding basis, delivery option \\
SPY $\leftrightarrow$ QQQ (correlated) & Bond $\leftrightarrow$ credit ETF (sector exposure) & Large: single-name vs.\ portfolio \\
--- & 5Y bond $\leftrightarrow$ 10Y bond (same issuer) & Medium: curve risk, liquidity diff \\
--- & Senior $\leftrightarrow$ sub bond (same issuer) & Very large: capital structure risk \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

The key insight: in equities, the conversion residual is negligible (basis points of basis points). In bonds, the conversion residual is often the same order of magnitude as the bid-ask spread you're trying to capture. This means the cross-instrument lean in bonds is structurally noisier, and the lean must carry explicit uncertainty estimates.

\subsection{Price Space $\to$ Spread Space}

This is the deepest difference and the one with no equity analogue.

In equities, aggregation happens in price space because a dollar is a dollar --- there are no coupon, maturity, or optionality effects distorting the price. A share of NVDA at \$185 on Exchange A and \$185 on Exchange B is the same thing.

In bonds, dollar price is a nonlinear, time-varying function of the underlying credit spread. Two bonds at the same spread can have very different prices due to coupon differences. A bond's price changes overnight from carry and pull-to-par even if its spread hasn't moved. Convexity means that a 10bp spread widening moves the price differently than a 10bp tightening.

Therefore: \textbf{the lean must aggregate in spread space, not price space.} All observations are converted to spread (Z-spread, OAS, or hazard rate) before cleaning or weighting. The conversion back to price happens only at the final step, using the target bond's specific analytics. This separation ensures that coupon, maturity, optionality, and time effects are handled correctly.

\subsection{Summary: The Translation}

\begin{specbox}[The Bond Lean in One Sentence]
Collect every observable data point about a bond's credit spread --- from TRACE, RFQ platforms, CDS, ETFs, and related bonds --- convert each to spread, clean and weight by freshness and reliability, aggregate into a single best estimate, and convert to price only when quoting a specific bond using that bond's own analytics.
\end{specbox}


