\section{The Lean Space}\label{sec:space}
% ============================================================

All aggregation operates in one of three spread representations, chosen per bond based on instrument availability:

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{@{}lll@{}}
\toprule
\textbf{Lean Space} & \textbf{When to Use} & \textbf{Why} \\
\midrule
Z-spread & Bullet bonds without liquid CDS & Simplest; no optionality or CDS to reconcile \\
OAS & Callable bonds & Strips out the call option value \\
Hazard rate & Any name with liquid CDS & Natural common currency between CDS and cash \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

\textbf{Why spread, not price.} A spread observation from 2 hours ago is still a valid credit observation --- the issuer's credit risk hasn't been contaminated by the passage of time, carry, or rates movement. A \textit{price} observation from 2 hours ago is stale because the benchmark curve has moved, accrued interest has changed, and pull-to-par has advanced. Working in spread space eliminates an entire category of time-adjustment errors.

\textbf{Conversion to price} happens once, at the moment of quoting, using the target bond's own coupon schedule, maturity, call structure, day count, and the current benchmark curve. This is where all the bond-specific complexity lives --- and it's handled by a standard bond pricer, not by the lean engine.


% ============================================================
\section{Data Sources and Their Information Content}\label{sec:sources}
% ============================================================

\subsection{Source Hierarchy}

When all sources are fresh, the typical reliability ordering is:

\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=2em]
  \item \textbf{Own RFQ fills/responses.} Direct, competitive, firm prices. Highest quality but sparse.
  \item \textbf{TRACE prints $<$15 min old.} Realized transactions. High quality but one-sided (bid or offer, not mid), size-capped, and delayed.
  \item \textbf{CDS quotes.} Continuous, dealer-to-dealer market. Tight basis for liquid names, but the CDS--bond basis is itself uncertain and regime-dependent.
  \item \textbf{Related bond leans} (same issuer, adjacent maturity). Informative when the source bond is liquid. Requires a structured conversion with multiple adjustment terms.
  \item \textbf{Composite quotes} (CP+, Ai-Price). Aggregated dealer indications. Smoothed, potentially stale, indicative not firm.
  \item \textbf{ETF-derived lean.} High frequency (exchange-traded) but wide conversion residual. Best as a directional anchor, not a precision price.
  \item \textbf{Dealer axes/runs.} Directional signal only. Not suitable as a price anchor.
\end{enumerate}

This ordering \textbf{inverts} when same-bond data goes stale. If the last TRACE print is 3 hours old but CDS is live, CDS dominates the lean. The weighting system must handle this dynamically.


% ============================================================
\section{Cleaning Each Source}\label{sec:cleaning}
% ============================================================

Every raw observation is transformed into a \textbf{mid-spread estimate with a reliability weight}. The cleaning differs by source type.

\subsection{TRACE Prints}

TRACE data has specific biases that must be corrected before use.

\textbf{Capped sizes.} FINRA disseminates trade size capped at \$5MM (IG) and \$1MM (HY). A reported \$5MM+ trade could be \$5MM or \$50MM. Use an expected-size correction: $\mathbb{E}[s \mid s \geq s_{\text{cap}}] \approx 2.5 \times s_{\text{cap}}$ (calibrate from uncapped data if available). Feed the corrected size into the half-spread model.

\textbf{Side correction.} A customer-buy print is at the offer. Convert to mid-spread by adding the half-spread (in spread space, adding half-spread widens the spread, which is the direction from offer toward mid):

\begin{equation}
\hat{s}_{\text{mid}} = s_{\text{print}} + \text{side} \times \hat{h}_{\mathcal{R}}(\text{corrected\_size})
\end{equation}

where $\text{side} = -1$ for customer-buy (print is at tighter spread / offer), $+1$ for customer-sell (print is at wider spread / bid). $\hat{h}_{\mathcal{R}}$ is the half-spread model specific to the bond's liquidity regime (Section~\ref{sec:liquidity}).

\textbf{Flow pressure correction.} TRACE prints are not independent draws from a distribution centered on mid. If the last 5 prints are all customer-sells, the sell-prints are likely at wider-than-equilibrium spreads (the street is being forced to buy and is charging for it). Apply a conditional correction:

\begin{equation}
\hat{s}_{\text{adj}} = \hat{s}_{\text{mid}} - \delta_{\text{pressure}} \times \text{side} \times \hat{h}
\end{equation}

where $\delta_{\text{pressure}} \in [0, 0.3]$ is estimated from the recent directional imbalance in the TRACE tape (trailing buy/sell ratio, same-side clustering, corroborating CDS/ETF direction).

\textbf{Staleness weighting.} Spread observations decay in value with age:

\begin{equation}
w_{\text{age}} = \exp\!\left(-\frac{(t - t_k) \ln 2}{\tau_{\text{trace}}}\right)
\end{equation}

with $\tau_{\text{trace}} = 30$ min for IG, 60 min for HY. Hard cutoff at 4 hours (after which the print contributes zero).

\textbf{Size weighting.} Larger trades are more informative: $w_{\text{size}} = (s / s_{\text{ref}})^{0.4}$, using corrected size for capped prints.

\textbf{Noise inflation.} TRACE does not report dealer identity. Some fraction of prints represent off-market or relationship trades. Inflate the observation noise by $1.3\times$ to account for this.

\textbf{Final weight:} $w = w_{\text{age}} \times w_{\text{size}} \times \omega_{\text{trace}}$ where $\omega_{\text{trace}}$ is the source base weight.


\subsection{Composite Quotes}

\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=2em]
  \item Convert bid/ask prices to bid/ask spreads using the bond's analytics and current curve.
  \item Compute mid-spread: $s_{\text{comp}} = (s_{\text{bid}} + s_{\text{offer}}) / 2$.
  \item De-lag: $\hat{s} = s_{\text{comp}} + \beta_{\text{delag}} \times (s_{\text{comp}} - s_{\text{comp,prev}})$, where $\beta_{\text{delag}} \approx 0.3$ (calibrated from composite-vs-next-fill regressions).
  \item Assign weight: $w = \omega_{\text{composite}} \times \mathbb{1}[\text{age} < 120\text{s}]$.
\end{enumerate}


\subsection{Own RFQ History}

Convert fills to spread. Apply the same side/half-spread correction as TRACE. Assign high base weight ($\omega_{\text{rfq}} = 0.9$) because these are competitive, firm prices. Age-weight with a shorter halflife ($\tau = 20$ min) since RFQ data reveals the live competitive landscape.


\subsection{CDS Quotes}

CDS is natively in spread. If operating in hazard-rate space, convert: $h = s_{\text{cds}} / (1 - R)$.

The bond's spread differs from CDS by the \textbf{basis}:
\begin{equation}
\hat{s}_{\text{bond}} = s_{\text{cds}} + \hat{b}(t)
\end{equation}

Initialize the basis from the most recent same-bond observation: $\hat{b}(t_0) = s_{\text{bond,last}} - s_{\text{cds}}(t_0)$. As the observation ages, decay the basis toward its long-run estimate:
\begin{equation}
\hat{b}(t) = \hat{b}(t_0) \cdot e^{-\kappa_b (t - t_0)} + \bar{b} \cdot (1 - e^{-\kappa_b(t - t_0)})
\end{equation}

Assign weight using the regime-conditional conversion uncertainty (Section~\ref{sec:basis}).


\subsection{Related Bonds (Same Issuer)}

For a source bond $X$ with a fresh lean, estimate the target bond $Y$'s spread via:
\begin{equation}
\hat{s}_Y = s_X + \Delta_{\text{curve}} + \Delta_{\text{senior}} + \Delta_{\text{call}} + \Delta_{\text{liq}} + \Delta_{\text{struct}}
\end{equation}

Each adjustment term is described in Section~\ref{sec:hetero}. Assign weight inversely proportional to the conversion uncertainty, which increases with the number of active adjustment terms and the magnitude of each.


\subsection{ETF-Derived Lean}

Compute the implied spread change from the ETF return since the last known same-bond observation:
\begin{equation}
\Delta \hat{s}_Y = -\frac{\beta_{Y,\text{etf}} \times \Delta P_{\text{etf}}}{\text{DV01}_Y}
\end{equation}

Apply to last known spread: $\hat{s}_Y = s_{Y,\text{last}} + \Delta \hat{s}_Y$. Assign low weight (wide conversion residual: 5--15bps IG, 15--40bps HY).


% ============================================================
\section{Bond Heterogeneity: The Conversion Model}\label{sec:hetero}
% ============================================================

When leaning from one bond to another by the same issuer, the conversion is \textbf{not} a simple additive offset. Bonds differ along six dimensions, each requiring explicit treatment:

\begin{equation}
\boxed{\;\hat{s}_Y = s_X + \Delta_{\text{curve}}(T_X, T_Y) + \Delta_{\text{senior}} + \Delta_{\text{call}} + \Delta_{\text{liq}} + \Delta_{\text{struct}} + \epsilon\;}
\end{equation}

\textbf{Term structure} $\Delta_{\text{curve}}$: the spread difference between the source and target maturity points on the issuer's credit curve. Estimated from the CDS term structure (if liquid), historical bond-vs-bond differentials, or the average curve shape for the rating/sector cohort.

\textbf{Seniority} $\Delta_{\text{senior}}$: senior unsecured vs.\ subordinated vs.\ secured. Estimated from cross-sectional lookup by rating and seniority. In distress, this term dominates and becomes highly unstable --- the capital structure trades on recovery, not spread.

\textbf{Optionality} $\Delta_{\text{call}}$: callable vs.\ bullet, par call vs.\ make-whole. Computed from the OAS model. Make-whole provisions are less valuable to the issuer, so the adjustment is smaller.

\textbf{Liquidity} $\Delta_{\text{liq}}$: on-the-run premium, index-eligibility effect, ETF inclusion, issue-size effect. See Section~\ref{sec:liquidity}.

\textbf{Structural} $\Delta_{\text{struct}}$: covenant differences, repo specialness, currency/jurisdiction effects. Estimated from cross-sectional regressions, updated infrequently.

\textbf{Residual} $\epsilon$: everything else. The standard deviation of $\epsilon$ is the conversion uncertainty and directly determines the lean weight for this source.

\begin{warnbox}[When to Disable Cross-Bond Leans]
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
  \item Source and target differ in seniority: reduce weight 50--70\%.
  \item Issuer in distress (CDS $>$ 500bps): capital structure trades on recovery. All cross-bond relationships break. Disable.
  \item Maturity difference $>$10Y: curve extrapolation is unreliable. Reduce weight 40--60\%.
\end{itemize}
\end{warnbox}


% ============================================================
\section{Liquidity Regimes}\label{sec:liquidity}
% ============================================================

Liquidity in credit is clustered, not continuous. A single half-spread model is insufficient. The half-spread depends on the bond's position in a multi-dimensional liquidity landscape:

\textbf{On-the-run vs.\ off-the-run.} The most recently issued bond at a given maturity point trades dramatically tighter and more liquid. When a new bond is issued, the previous one widens by 5--20bps overnight.

\textbf{Index-eligible vs.\ non-eligible.} Bonds in major indices (Bloomberg US Agg, Bloomberg IG Corporate) receive forced demand from index trackers. They trade 3--10bps tighter and 2--3$\times$ higher volume.

\textbf{ETF inclusion.} Bonds held by LQD, HYG, etc.\ have additional liquidity from the AP creation/redemption mechanism.

\textbf{New issue vs.\ seasoned.} Newly issued bonds ($<$30 days) have elevated volume. After 30--90 days, volume drops 70--90\%.

\textbf{Issue size.} Bonds with $<$\$300MM outstanding are structurally illiquid. The relationship between size and cost is nonlinear.

Each bond is assigned a \textbf{liquidity regime} $\mathcal{R}(i)$ based on these features, and the half-spread model is fitted separately per regime:

\begin{equation}
\hat{h}_{\mathcal{R}}(s, \sigma_t) = h_{0,\mathcal{R}} + h_{s,\mathcal{R}} \cdot s^{0.4} + h_{\sigma,\mathcal{R}} \cdot \sigma_t
\end{equation}

where $s$ is trade size and $\sigma_t$ is current market volatility (MOVE index). The concave power on size ($s^{0.4}$) reflects the empirical sublinear relationship between size and execution cost.


% ============================================================
\section{Basis Risk and Tail Behavior}\label{sec:basis}
% ============================================================

Every cross-instrument lean carries basis risk: the conversion residual between the source and target instrument. In equities, this residual is negligible. In bonds, it is material and \textbf{non-Gaussian, negatively skewed, and regime-dependent}.

\subsection{Why Gaussian Is Dangerous}

The CDS--bond basis, ETF tracking error, and cross-bond spreads all exhibit:

\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
  \item \textbf{Fat tails.} Blowouts are much larger and more frequent than a Gaussian predicts.
  \item \textbf{Asymmetry.} In stress, bases \textit{widen} (CDS--bond basis becomes more negative, ETFs trade at discount). The blowout is directional.
  \item \textbf{Clustering.} Large moves beget large moves. Basis volatility is persistent.
  \item \textbf{Correlation.} All bases blow out simultaneously in stress (driven by common funding/balance sheet shocks), exactly when you need the lean most.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Basis Model}

Use either a \textbf{regime-switching Gaussian} or a \textbf{Student-$t$ with GARCH dynamics}:

\textbf{Option 1: Regime-switching.}
\begin{equation}
\epsilon(t) \mid r_t \sim \begin{cases}
\mathcal{N}(\mu_{\text{calm}}, \sigma^2_{\text{calm}}) & r_t = \text{calm} \\
\mathcal{N}(\mu_{\text{stress}}, \sigma^2_{\text{stress}}) & r_t = \text{stressed}
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

with $\sigma_{\text{stress}} \approx 3$--$5 \times \sigma_{\text{calm}}$ and $\mu_{\text{stress}} > 0$ (directional blowout). The regime probability is driven by observable indicators:
\begin{equation}
P(\text{stress} \mid \mathbf{z}_t) = \sigma\!\left(\beta_0 + \beta_{\text{MOVE}} \cdot \text{MOVE} + \beta_{\text{VIX}} \cdot \text{VIX} + \beta_{\text{CDX}} \cdot \text{CDX.IG} + \beta_{\text{QE}} \cdot \mathbb{1}[\text{quarter-end}]\right)
\end{equation}

\textbf{Option 2: Student-$t$ / GARCH.}
\begin{equation}
\epsilon(t) \sim t_\nu(\mu(t), \sigma^2(t)), \qquad \sigma^2(t) = \omega + \alpha \epsilon^2(t-1) + \beta \sigma^2(t-1) + \gamma \cdot \text{MOVE}_t
\end{equation}

with $\nu \approx 3$--$6$ (fat tails), capturing volatility clustering and stress dependence.

\subsection{Impact on Lean Weights}

The lean weight for any cross-instrument source uses the \textbf{current regime-conditional} variance:
\begin{equation}
w_s(t) = \omega_{\text{base},s} \times w_{\text{freshness}} \times \frac{1}{1 + (\sigma_{\text{conv},s}(t) / \sigma_{\text{ref}})^2}
\end{equation}

In calm markets, $\sigma_{\text{conv}} \approx 2$bps and the weight is high. In stress, $\sigma_{\text{conv}} \approx 15$bps and the weight collapses. Additionally, enforce a hard cap: the total weight from cross-instrument sources cannot exceed $\theta_{\text{cross,max}}(r_t)$ (0.8 in calm, 0.5 in stress).


