\section{Testing the Lean}\label{sec:testing}
% ============================================================

A lean is only useful if it predicts where you can actually trade.

\subsection{Test 1: Lean-vs-Fill Accuracy}

For every observed fill (your own RFQs or TRACE prints), compute:
\begin{equation}
e_k = s_{\text{fill},k} - s_{\text{lean}}(t_k)
\end{equation}

All errors are in spread space (eliminates convexity/coupon artifacts). Report:

\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
  \item \textbf{Bias} $\bar{e}$: should be near zero.
  \item \textbf{RMSE}: overall accuracy. Target: 1--3bps for liquid IG (calm); 10--25bps for illiquid HY (stress).
  \item \textbf{Hit rate}: fraction of fills where $|e| < 3$bps. Target: $>$70\% for liquid IG.
\end{itemize}

Segment by: lean confidence, time since last same-bond observation, liquidity regime, market regime (calm/stressed), trade size, and dominant lean source.

\subsection{Test 2: Hedge Efficacy}

The acid test for cross-instrument leans. You quote $Y$ off a lean derived from instrument $X$, get filled, and hedge by trading $X$. The hedge slippage is:
\begin{equation}
\text{slippage} = (s_{\text{fill}} - s_{\text{lean}}) - (s_{\text{hedge}} - s_X) \times \frac{\partial Y}{\partial X}
\end{equation}

Report: mean slippage (should be positive --- you capture spread), slippage vol, and the Sharpe of the quote-hedge cycle. If Sharpe $< 0$, the lean is costing you money through that source.

\subsection{Test 3: Source Ablation}

Drop each source one at a time and measure accuracy degradation. This tells you where to invest modeling effort.

\subsection{Test 4: Spread Calibration}

Compare the lean half-spread $\hat{h}$ against realized execution costs from TRACE. If the lean spread is systematically too tight, you'll be adversely selected. If too wide, you're quoting uncompetitively.

\subsection{Test 5: Conversion Stability}

Track each cross-instrument conversion residual over time. If the residual is persistent (high AR(1)), the conversion parameters are drifting and need recalibration. If residual vol spikes in stress, the lean should automatically downweight that source (check that it does).

\subsection{Test 6: P\&L Attribution}

Backtest with two configurations: full lean vs.\ naive lean (most recent TRACE mid only). The P\&L difference is the marginal value of the lean infrastructure.

\subsection{Test 7: Tail Accuracy}

Compute errors on the subset of observations where the basis model indicated stress. Report 5th/95th percentiles, not just RMSE. The lean may be well-calibrated on average but dangerously wrong in the tails.

\begin{specbox}[What ``Good'' Looks Like]
\begin{tabular}{@{}lll@{}}
\toprule
\textbf{Metric} & \textbf{Liquid IG (calm)} & \textbf{Illiquid HY (stress)} \\
\midrule
Bias & $<$ 0.5 bps & $<$ 5 bps \\
RMSE & 1--3 bps & 10--25 bps \\
95th pctile error & $<$ 5 bps & $<$ 40 bps \\
Hit rate ($<$3bps) & $>$70\% & $>$30\% \\
Hedge cycle Sharpe & $>$2.0 & $>$0.5 \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{specbox}


